tsu: yac'ʉ ta ateoyono 'oyona tmopsʉ 'o sooto Chai In Un ho mi'osno ta soezopʉ no coo ho eovei
english: President Tsai Ing-wen's Apology to the Indigenous Peoples on Behalf of the Government.

tsu: to nia aoyosi no tomposka oeso. 'o senfa isi sopohngi hoco teovahi ne ohec'ola yainca "yata foengo"'e coo ta taivang hoco poa "anana'o yatan'e ci coo,"'emo maica totohci ta ongko, o'a isi anova saapayo'a na noana'o cimo yaa potfngʉ ci pat'aona. isin'a epopayoa ho zoo atohco yata taivang 'e soezop no coo. i'tohongo tan'e. teto toehongo m'esohco maitan'e. te'o yac'ʉ ta ateono 'oyona tmopsʉ maitan'e, boemi no mʉ'eona ta 'tohʉngʉ ho mi'osno ta acʉcʉhʉ ci soezopʉ no coo ta taivang ho eovei. ina ohola miya ci tose'sʉpta ci hie. mimo smovei no ma'totomzo ho 'oha ahmxskʉ cila ti'a'aosna, te'o yac'ʉ ta ateono 'oyona tmopsʉ ho mi'osno moo ho eovei.
english: On this day 22 years ago, the term "shanbao" (mountain people) in the Additional Articles of our Constitution was replaced with the proper name: "indigenous people." This correction not only did away with a discriminatory term, but also highlighted the status of indigenous peoples as Taiwan's "original owners." From this basis, today, we are taking another step forward. To all indigenous peoples of Taiwan: On behalf of the government, I express to you our deepest apology. For the four centuries of pain and mistreatment you have endured, I apologize to you on behalf of the government.

tsu: os'o taa'ozva, ac'ʉhʉ maitan'e, ta aokokoyongo ta h'oyonsovato, mioc'on'a yaa maica ci 'tohʉngʉ o'ante 'ahʉyʉ eovei. 'aeno na eni, na te'o koa asohco yac'ʉ ta ateono 'oyona tmopsʉ ho eovei. lahe yainca no koyohe, 'o niala 'oha ahmʉskʉ hocieno na nia 'atotomzo to mocmo ci soezopʉ 'alaeno anana'va esmiza hote yosohci 'e yatatiskova. na eni temza yac'ʉ tan'e, ta'koeva no aezoha ho taiezoha 'emo maica ci hia ma'to'tohʉngʉ.
english: I know that even now, there are some around us who see no need to apologize. But that is the most important reason why I am representing the government to issue this apology today. To see what was unfair in the past as a matter of course, or to treat the pain of other ethnic peoples as an unavoidable part of human development, this is the first mindset that we, standing here today, resolve to change and overturn.

tsu: te'o titho tate ta'hongi ci e'e ho pateafa na koa mi'osno ta soezopʉ no coo ta taivang ho eovei. 'e ceoa ta taivang, aoyosi no tose'sʉpta mohcola yaa nooyo ci yatatiskova. 'emo maica ci yatatiskova mosola anana'o yaa iachi h'oyonsova, yaa iachi h'oe'eya, h'oceoceona, at'oca ci hopa. acngoho, moso yono o'amoso yopa tohmʉskʉ ci 'tohʉngʉ, moso esmi ta ceoa tan'e 'omo h'oasi ci soezopʉ, to a'a'aosna ne aoyosi, 'emo oafeihi ci coo oheco
english: Let me put in simple terms why we are apologizing to the indigenous peoples. Four hundred years ago, there were already people living in Taiwan. These first inhabitants lived their lives and had their own languages, cultures, customs, and domains. But then, without their consent, another group of people arrived on these shores, and in the course of history, took everything from the first inhabitants who, on the land they have known most intimately, became displaced, foreign, non-mainstream, and marginalized.

tsu: ti'einga 'e acʉcʉhʉ ta moso nooyo ci coo. poa meaapapayo'ʉ ta ohela atva'esa at'oca ci ceoa. nama micoc'o mais'a yano yafana. o'a na atohcosi ho coc'o poasaskita ci coo. hola meelʉ biʉlʉlʉ emo coni ci soezopʉ, asonʉ na'nosi p'eac'a no 'atotomio no mocmo ci soezopʉ, mac'oci o'te 'ahʉyʉ iachi mainca zoo moolʉlʉ ci hpʉhpʉngʉ, o'ate peelʉi o'te mipo'ʉ'ʉmti ho esansana na nia a'ʉmtʉsi ne aoyosi, ataveisi, nate sotva'esa, 'e;oyonatmopsx te asansano nomio no niala aoyosi ho yaa moo'ʉmtʉ ci ma'vovei, 'aeno eni na koa'o yac'ʉ tan'e maitan'e.
english: The success of one ethnic people can be built on the suffering of another. Unless we deny that we are a country of justice, we must face up to this history. We must tell the truth. And then, most importantly, the government must genuinely reflect on this past. This is why I stand here today.

tsu: panto conci tposʉ isi yainca (tposx no aoyosi ta taivang), isi engha to ehoisi ho yainca: (ok'a ci nia aoyosi ta taivang. ohe paavi to 'olan, hioa to teizi, yaezoya to seizi.) 'aeno eni na lahe hia baito no nia aoyosi ta taivang to pooto. 'e soezopʉ no coo, aoyosi no toposifoo, mohcola 'aoesiesi yayo ta ceoa tan'e, mo iachi yaa atngaso ci h'oceoceona ho mootʉs'ʉ, ho yo'ticngicngiha. at'inghi lac'o i'mi no bitaso ci hia baito ho tposi 'e nia aoyosi, nomio tan'e, te'o yac'ʉ ta ateono 'oyona tmopsʉ ho mi'osno ta soezopʉ no coo ho eovei.
english: There is a book called "The General History of Taiwan" published in 1920. In its foreword are these words: "Taiwan had no history. The Dutch pioneered it, the Koxinga Kingdom built it, and the Qing Empire managed it." This is a typical Han view of history. The truth is that indigenous peoples have been here for thousands of years, with rich culture and wisdom that have been passed down through generations. But we only know to write history from the perspective of the dominant. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

tsu: 'oniaseizi to'olan hoteisekoo ohe ake'a potpapayo'a 'o soezopʉ to peepoa ho pa'mamaesih'a na ohela noe'oci no h'oyonsovahe, na nia meoino yo'tihmohmoyo ho pohcingha to mansei, ho ine ohecola aʉt'ʉca to maaya ho ohmʉs'onʉ ta coo ho yainca te tasocza ci seisako, ac'ʉhʉ ne oheco tioska ta pooto ne apihana 'e hxpxhxpxxngx, ho 'ahʉhʉya poa boa pooto 'e coo ta 'ayomonasi ta tose'sʉpta, cono hola esmi 'emo cono soezopʉ, la boepapak'i ho pohcinghi, tophohco ta ceoa, a'ʉmta koici akozkozoa 'e mosola anana'o yayo ci kenli, nomio tan'e, te'o yac'ʉ ta ateono 'oyona tmopsʉ ho mi'osno ta soezopʉ no coo ho eovei.
english: The Dutch and the Koxinga Kingdom massacred and exploited the Pingpu ethnic group. The Qing Empire presided over bloody confrontations and suppression. Colonial Japan put in place comprehensive savage policies. And the post- war ROC government undertook assimilation policies. For 400 years, every regime that has come to Taiwan has brutally violated the rights of indigenous peoples through armed invasion and land seizure. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

tsu: 'e soezopʉ no coo la fiho to iachi h'oceoceona ho ko'ko tmoteoyono 'e cono hosa, a'vinano fiho to mootʉs'ʉ ci h'oceoceona ho meelʉ e'tatiski na maonsonsoo ta 'oyona. at'inghi, yonta 'ayomona ho isi seolʉa no p'eyac'a 'emo faeva ci hpʉhpʉngʉ, isi payo'a ta soezopʉ no coo na kenli no iyachi esvʉtʉ ho iyachi aʉt'ʉcʉ. mico aemo'ʉ na niala t'ʉcna no tmoteoyono, o'anala tiova ta meoino hʉpʉhpʉʉngʉ na ohola toehonga tae'oci. nomio tan'e, te'o yac'ʉ ta ateono 'oyona tmopsʉ ho mi'osno ta soezopʉ ta coo ho eovei.
english: Indigenous peoples maintain tribal order according to traditional customs, and ecological balance according to traditional wisdom. But in the process of modern state-building, indigenous peoples lost the right to steer their own course and govern their own affairs. The fabric of traditional societies was torn apart, and the collective rights of peoples were not recognized. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

tsu: 'e soezopʉ no coo mosola iyachi yaa h'oe'eya, nocaefi to maaya ho ohela aʉt'ʉca ho ocia poa tmomaaya, ho ine ataveisi no moso 1945, ohela potani ta seifo 'e coo hocin'a boacoo, co i'mizi no meoino aapayo'ʉ 'e iyachi h'oe'ea. aavaho i'o ohola yainca peepoa ci soezopʉ, mico a'ʉmta aʉlʉ aapapayo'ʉ 'o nia e'ehe. 'omosola afo'o aʉt' ʉcʉ ne aoyosi, o'a ohola peispo'ʉ'ʉmti na poa tʉyʉcneni na h'oceoceona ta soezopʉ no coo. nomio tan'e, te'o yac'ʉ ta ateono 'oyona tmopsʉ ho mi'osno ta soezopʉ ta coo ho eovei.
english: Indigenous peoples had their own languages. However, with Japanese rule aiming to assimilate and turn all into imperial subjects, and with the ROC government banning tribal languages after 1945, indigenous peoples' languages suffered great losses. Most Pingpu languages have disappeared. Successive governments have been negligent in the protection of indigenous cultures. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

tsu: ne mihnan'a, yono o'a ihe cohivi ci a'a'aosna to soezopʉ to taa'o, 'e seifo ohe soʉlʉlʉa to lahe yoni ci ceoa 'o caciha no mahiz'o ci poco, poa svieni ta soezopʉ to taa'o na ma'sasmoyo no mahiz'o, nomio tan'e, te'o yac'ʉ ta ateono 'oyona tmopsʉ ho mi'osno ta soezopʉ to taa'o ho eovei.
english: Without the knowledge of the Yami tribe, the government stored nuclear waste on Orchid Island. Tribe members on the island had to suffer the negative consequences. For this, I apologize to the Yami people on behalf of the government.

tsu: ahoi ho mohco yʉmeʉmʉ ta taivang 'o yane yafana, i'o mosola yonta maoponeo ta meoveana ci soezopʉ no peepoa oho atva'esa aoeva noa potpapayo'a. ohela aʉt'ʉca ho aapayo'a na ongko nohe cono soezopʉ, nomio tan'e, to taa'o ho mi'osno ta soezopʉ ta peepoa ho eovei.
english: Ever since outsiders began arriving in Taiwan, the Pingpu ethnic group on the western plains have born the brunt of the impact. One ruling power after another eroded the individual and collective identities of the Pingpu ethnic group. For this, I apologize to the Pingpu ethnic group on behalf of the government.

tsu: la yainca zoo meoi no hʉpʉhpʉʉngʉ no atvohʉ ci h'oceoceo 'e taivang. at'inghi ac'ʉhʉ maitan'e, na yoayokeo, ma'cohio, h'oyonsova no keizai, peis'opo no seizi, mioc'on'a asngʉcʉ askocohe ta o'a soezopʉ no coo. a'vinano 'o anana'o potfʉnga ci hiahe baito ta soezopʉ no coo. o'amo ahto aapayo'ʉ. o'amo amso man'i nala hioa ta 'oyona tmopsʉ, poa tioo no o'a ohela esmiza to mocmo ci soezopʉ ci ma'totomzo, nomio tan'e, te'o yac'ʉ ta ateono 'oyona tmopsʉ ho mi'osno ta soezopʉ ta coo ho eovei.
english: Taiwan is known as a culturally diverse society. But even today, indicators on health, education, economic livelihood, political participation and more still show gaps between indigenous and non- indigenous peoples. Meanwhile, stereotypes and even discrimination against indigenous peoples have not gone away. The government has not done enough, so indigenous peoples have suffered pain and frustration unknown to other ethnic peoples. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

tsu: o'a mimza amso bototaso, a'vinano aocngicngihi o'te osnia hosansana ho o'amimza bototaso, ko'koeno ac'ʉhʉ maitan'e ho poa elʉa no 'atotomzo 'e feangomo. a'ʉmtʉs'a pa'hikokoe'i. 'e eovei maitan'e, e'vono mico na'no poha'o, at'inghi te yainca zoo ahoisi. o'a os'o yainca tesiscos'a aososeoma ta moc'o matnʉskʉ ci tposʉ no eovei na nia alolongʉ no tose'sʉpta. at'inghi te'o i'mʉs'oneni ta 'tohʉng'o ho mingeovi, 'e eovei maitan'e, zoo ahoisi no emo'osno no nananghingiya 'e 'ayomona tamo cono hpʉhpʉngʉ.
english: Our efforts have fallen short, and succeeding generations have been blind to this inadequacy. Because of this, your hardship has continued to this day. For this we are truly sorry. Today's apology is long overdue, but it is a beginning. I do not expect any one speech or phrase of apology to wipe away four centuries of pain and suffering by the indigenous peoples. But I do hope with all my heart that today's apology will set this country and all its people on the path towards reconciliation.

tsu: teomneni te'o boemi ta mootʉs'ʉ no soezopʉ no coo ho esansana 'e hia noteoyono maitan'e. to e'e to taiyalo 'o la yainca balay. 'o la yainca sbalay. 'e aoyosi ta balay isi sopohngi ta S. 'e ho mo natʉ'ca ci hia ma'to'tohʉngʉ, pateivha, na a'ʉmtʉ no eosʉseomʉ, te i'mi no mipo'ʉ'ʉmti na a'ʉmtʉsi niante peelʉi peihcʉ'hi.
english: Please allow me to shed light on this occasion with a piece of indigenous wisdom. In the Atayal language, truth is called "Balay," and reconciliation is called "Sbalay," so you simply add an "S" sound to "Balay." Truth and reconciliation are in fact two related concepts. In other words, only by facing the truth sincerely can reconciliation be attained.

tsu: to h'oceoceona ta soezopʉ no coo, 'e cono hosa, hoci yaa 'oha eino ho elolongʉ no mocmo, hoci mainca no koyo te mici eososeomʉ, 'o mamameoi lahe eteoyona 'omo akozkozo ho i'o isi akozkozoa, poa noepohʉ aʉlʉ yopa mi'osno ho eʉsvʉta na nia a'ʉmtʉ 'tohʉngʉ, ataveisi ho isoco esansana na 'tohʉngʉ, tena toehongo pesonʉ tomo cono soetohvʉ ci emi, poaco socaefi 'e mohco nocaefi ci hi'hioa, 'aeno eni na isi yainca.
english: In indigenous cultures, when a tribe member has offended another and intends to reconcile, an elder brings together the offender and the offended - not to produce a direct apology, but to allow each side to frankly share their inner journeys. When this truth-telling concludes, the elder calls for everyone to drink together, so that what is past is truly past. This is "Sbalay."

tsu: te'o totea 'e hioa maitan'e, 'aeno te meelʉ 'e 'oyona tmopsʉ ho i'e soezopx no coo. pnanfi na tonʉ ho esansana na niala peis'epo, na nia a'ʉmtʉsi, ok'a eyava ho esansana. ho aomane, 'o nanghia'o ta soezopʉ no coo tesi yaeza eh'ʉta na 'tohʉngʉsi. o'ate'o smeecʉ'ho m'ea peo'ozva maitan'e, at'inghi te'o tata'ia temo ma'eʉyʉcʉ ho mingeovi, na niala peis'epo ne noana'o o'anate i'vaha peisvahi, 'e hpʉhpʉngʉ eni, tenala yaa hiesi, meelʉ
english: I hope today's occasion can be a "Sbalay" between the government and the indigenous peoples. I have spoken of past mistakes and truths the best I can, with nothing held back. In a moment, our indigenous friends will speak. I do not dare ask you to forgive, here and now. But I sincerely ask you to sustain the hope that past wrongs will not be repeated, and that one day, this country can see true reconciliation.

tsu: a'ʉmtʉ emo'osno no eososeomʉ. 'e maitan'e tec'on'a yainca ahoisi, nate smovei no eososeomʉ o'ate tomakneni ta soezopʉ no coo hocieno feango to soezopʉ to peepoa, mante yonta 'oyonatmopsʉ. os'o cohivi, hocic'o ngayoc'o na eososeomʉ o'ate ahto amso, acʉhʉ cite hioaneni ta soezopʉ no coo, zoo t'ʉcna no a'ʉmtʉ eososeomʉ ta hpʉhpʉngʉto.
english: Today is only a beginning. The duty for reconciliation lies not with the indigenous peoples and the Pingpu ethnic group, but with the government. I know that words of apology alone are not enough. What we actually do for the indigenous peoples will decide whether reconciliation succeeds or stumbles.

tsu: te'o yontan'e hoco a'ʉmta epeaska, 'e sotokofo te m'eyac'ʉ to (moolʉlʉ ci lekisi ho tmai'osno no moolʉlʉ ci 'i'in kai). te'o ieni ta ongkono'o tmooteoyona ta hpʉhpʉngʉ, iachia hioa na tela eoteoyono, toehongo na taihio to masosoezopʉ ho i'ima na moso moolʉlʉ ci nia aoyosi, maezo e'hahmʉskʉ toehonga toosvʉsvʉtʉ no tenala emo'aosna ta hpʉhpʉngʉ tan'e.
english: Therefore, I am here to announce that we are setting up an Indigenous Historical Justice and Transitional Justice Commission under the Presidential Office. As the head of state, I will serve as convener and work hand in hand with tribal representatives to pursue historical justice. We will also discuss, on the basis of equality, the future policy direction of this country.

tsu: te'o eho'a 'emo yontan'e, ho inamo baito no televi ho inamo bohmi no kanpioto ci soezopʉ no coo, teto toehonga hoomia. te'o eho'a na maananghia ho toehonga pocenga, o'ate yainca te epici. te'o noa sothi, pahsʉsʉfti, poa meelʉ peihcʉ'ho no ohola afo'a esvʉta ci hioa 'e 'oyona tmopsx, a'ʉmta teovahi na mosola o'te emzo no aoyosi.
english: To all of our indigenous friends here and watching on TV and online: I invite you to stand witness. I invite you not to endorse, but to oversee. Please keep pressure on the government and right its course where necessary, so that it will realize its commitments and right historical wrongs.

tsu: te'o to'aveoveoyʉ ta acʉcʉhʉ ci nanghia ta soezopʉ no coo, zoo moo na mimo e'sasmome ta afo'o yata hpʉhpʉngʉ tan'e, 'e isi p'ecihi ci ceoa, ho i'emo noana'o ci h'oceoceona, yayo na o'ate peelʉi peʉezi ci hophina. 'emo maica ci hophina, nate fii no so'einva.
english: I want to thank all of our indigenous friends. You remind everyone in this country that there is irreplaceable value in the land we tread on and the traditions we inherit. This value deserves dignity.

tsu: te'o noa toehongo bitotonʉ 'e aocono ci hpʉhpʉʉngʉ, honga 'e iachito aoyosi, honga 'e ceoato, yaeza honga na h'oceoceona tamo mav'ov'o ci soezopʉ. emo'osno no yopa naovei, emo'osno no tmocni ho toehongo psoevohngʉ, emo'osno note faeva ci taivan no ataveisi.
english: I call upon our entire society to come together and get to know our history, get to know our land, and get to know the cultures of our many ethnic peoples. Let us work towards reconciliation, a shared existence and shared prosperity, and a new future for Taiwan.

tsu: te'o m'ene ta acʉcʉhʉ ci 'oahngʉ ta cono hpʉhpʉngʉ, ieni tamo 'oc'ocic'o ci hie maitan'e, toehongo bitotonʉ ho m'eac'ʉ no conci moolʉlʉ ci hpʉhpʉngʉ, coni cimo ahmʉskʉ ho 'enepio no soezopʉ ci hpʉhpʉngʉ.
english: I call upon all citizens to seize the opportunities offered by this day - to join together, work hard, and build a country of justice, a country of true diversity and equality.

tsu: ci oko mo ea aʉt'ʉcʉ ta fo'konge.
english: A child had a pet frog.

tsu: ihe isi teapha ta pania si fo'konge.
english: He put the frog in the container.

tsu: mi co oengʉtʉ 'e oko no mamespingi ho 'e av'o.
english: The boy and the dog went to sleep.

tsu: 'iama mo eo eh yoyafo si fo'konge ho mimio.
english: The frog out (of the container) and went away.

tsu: mi co yʉc'ʉ 'e oko ho 'e av'o.
english: The boy and the dog got up.
has looked for the frog everywhere.

tsu: mi co mo oh ta enca pethʉ'ta ho eoho eoho'a 'e fo'konge.
english: went by the window and called at the frog.

tsu: o'a mo ahto tmalʉ mai maica mo oo eh ihe aka 'i'ima 'e fo'konge mico sopeohʉ si na si av'o.
english: They continuously looked for the frog. The dog fell (from the window).

tsu: smof'oyʉ si moso si m si 'o isi yoni ta fo'konge.
english: (The container) where the frog had been kept broke.

tsu: isi co ea ta oko no hahocngʉ ho pahas pasaha si av'o ho.
i'vaho oh ta mo asohco covhi ho 'i'ima 'e n na 'e fo'konge.
english: They proceeded again to look for the frog.

tsu: na 'e oko no hahocngʉ mo mi'osno ta ceoa ho eoho'ʉ.
english: The boy called toward the ground.

tsu: mi'osno ta mo feongo ci ceoa ho eoho'ʉʉ no fo'konge i'e av'o.
english: He called the frog through the hole in the ground. And the dog

tsu: mo mi'so mʉingʉcʉ ta evi ho eoho'ʉ at'inghi' i'e ihe i'e isi p'o'osni ta oko ci feongo 'iama zoo emo no bohci.
english: The child moved toward the hole in the ground, and it was a house of mouse.

tsu: ac'ohʉ si mo no ceoyʉ mico aemo'ʉ si inosi na 'e oko.
english: The beehive partly separated (from the tree). scattered.

tsu: mo m'o'osno ta feongo ta evi ho.
english: looked toward the hole in the tree.

tsu: 'iama mo ea nooyo ci poko ho.
mo yamci ho mo ea ea eoho'ʉ no fo'konge mi co smoyafo mi co iachi XyamXci 'e oko no hahocngʉ.
english: got frightened, and called the frog. came out. The boy got frightened.

tsu: na 'e av'o isi c'o n'a asʉngʉca peobanga ta na ita ceoyo ci ci isi taop tapeoha.
english: (The beehive) shaken and falling down the ground chased the dog.

tsu: na i'e oko no hahocngʉ isi peopa peobanga ta na ita.
poko mi co cocapo ho ta mo yohcoyo ci yohcoyo ho.
mo mici to totoefʉngʉ ta poko ho isi aka peobanga.
english: He wanted to hide from the owl which had kept chasing him.

tsu: oh ho eoho'a 'e eoho'a eoho'ʉ no fo'konge.
english: kept on calling for the frog.

tsu: 'iama 'iama 'iama zoo 'oa 'e isi capa ci mo mo yamci 'e na i'e 'oa mici isi co hafa smo'ono maita'e ho eh hafa mo'osno ta mo tʉ'nʉ.
english: The deer got frightened and carried him and ran toward the cliff.
The deer shook down the child.

tsu: mi co sopeohʉ 'e oko ho i'e av'o 'oc'ocic'o so' ta mo eachomoa.
english: The boy and the dog fell, and happen to fell into the water.

tsu: potani ta oko na 'e av'o ho eainca o'te ptaʉngʉ mais'a pan os'o talʉi ci fo'konge.
english: The boy told the dog not to be noisy. (The boy said): 'I seem to hear a frog.'
A tree happened to be there.

tsu: ihe co eokokoyongva ta na ita evi.
english: They looked for the frog around the tree.
(The boy suddenly realized that)it was together with (another frogs).

tsu: mi co aomane mi co maezo ea oso ci 'o'oko no fo'konge.
english: There were also small frogs that came.

tsu: ataveisi isi co enca ea 'e osi anana'va aʉt'ʉca ci fo'konge oho hafa maine'e.
english: Afterwards, he took his pet frog home.

tsu: pan no moso cihi ci oko no hahocngʉ.
moso n'a na'no kaebʉ ho mo oh no tonalisi ho noepohʉ na oko no mamespingi ho pespak'i.
english: liked to go to his neighbor and played with a girl.

tsu: ina oko no mamespingi moso n'a na'no kaebʉ emʉm'ʉ no bʉvnʉ mav'ov'o ci bʉvnʉ.
english: The girl liked to grow flowers very much, all kinds of flowers.

tsu: ina nia nana to'tohʉ no oko no mamespingi osi n'a la eainca ta'o la peongcʉngci no mo mav'ov'o ci bʉvnʉ 'e pahpaesa ta maemoemo.

tsu: 'a pasoya a'o, te'o miebini to mo'o.
english: I am pasuya, I am here for mo'o.

tsu: ba'i, mi'o esmi ho aopa'to soo.
english: Grandma, I am here to see you.

tsu: mikoco noana'o o'te oh tan'e, engha na'na talʉa na soo.
english: You haven't been here for a long time. I missed you so much.

tsu: tanivo, mi'o miebini soo ho mici peispak'i.
english: tanivu, I am here to play with you.

tsu: aopcio yʉmeʉmʉ, os'o aoka tote na soo.
english: Come on in! I have been waiting for you for a long time.

tsu: 'e os'o iachia emʉ'a ci f'oe, othoma.
english: This is the sweet potato I grow. Try it!
The sweet potato is so sweet.

tsu: oh tan'e, othoma 'e os'o iachia emʉ'a ci beahci no ana.
english: Come here! These are the fruits I grow. You should try it.

tsu: yosohngo! othoma 'e os'o emʉ'a ci pohe.
english: Take a seat! You should try some organic corn that I grow.
Wow! The corn tastes so sweet.

tsu: o'a la'o ʉmnʉ to hov'o, te'o bonʉ to linggo.
english: I can't eat oranges. I will have some apples instead.
Sure, I like it very much.

tsu: te'o s'eapocosi 'e te'o p'aeni ci beahci.
english: Let me peel the fruit for you.
Thank you. This fruit is so juicy.

tsu: te'o mayo to chomo no teko ima.
english: I will bring you some water.
Enjoy yourself. I cooked a lot of dishes.
Oh! It smells good and looks delicious.
Enjoy yourself. There is a lot more.
I'll make myself at home then.
Enjoy yourself. There are plenty here.
I ate a lot and couldn't eat any more.

tsu: te'o hafa ohne foengo na moo maitan'e.
english: I will take you to the mountains today.

tsu: isi yangca to ino mo man'i 'o mo'eocʉ.
english: Mom says that there are lots of mosquitoes in the mountains.

tsu: te'o hafa oh ne chana na moo maitan'e.
english: I will take you to the fields.
Are we going to loosen the soil?

tsu: tesi hafa ohne c'oeha to lema'cohio.
english: Teacher will take us to the riverside.

tsu: tesi hafa oh ne foengo to lema'cohio.
english: Teacher will take us to the mountains today.
Are we going to the riverside today?

tsu: o'a, tesi hafa oh ne foengo to lema'cohio.
english: No, our teacher is going to take us to the mountains.
Are we going to the mountains today?

tsu: o'a, teto oh ne chana maitan'e.
english: No, we are going to the fields.

tsu: lema'cohio, coma teto aiti ho teto oh ne c'oeha?
english: Teacher, what are we going to see at the riverside?
We are going to see dragonflies.

tsu: lema'cohio, coma teto aiti ho teto oh ne foengo?
english: Teacher, what are we going to see in the mountains?

tsu: teto oh ne'e ho baito to tokeoya.
english: We are going to see butterflies.

tsu: coma teto hioa ho teto oh ne chana?
english: What are we going to do in the fields?

tsu: teto oh ne chana ho aiti 'o ito emʉ'a ci pohe, bio'i'io 'sio to sosea ho teongo.
english: We are going to see the corn we grow in the fields, but you need to be aware of the ants and bees.

tsu: lema'cohio, teto yohngozo ho teto oh ne c'oeha?
english: Teacher, are we going to swim in the river?
No, we are going to see dragonflies.

tsu: lema'cohio, teto mʉemʉm'ʉ no chae ho teto oh ne chana?
english: Teacher, are we going to grow some vegetables in the fields?
We are going to loosen the soil today.

tsu: panto mo tohtoesoso ci tonvo ta'e.
mi'o petohʉyʉ baito ta mo yansoo ci tonvo.
english: Today is the first time I see real living dragonflies.

tsu: 'a eno, la'o ʉmnʉa 'o tokeoya, mo ʉmnʉ ho isi aiti.
english: Yeh! Wow! I love butterflies. They are very beautiful.
Those are not butterflies. They are bees.
Come here and take a look. Don't go too far!
Got it, we won't go anywhere too far.

tsu: 'ote peayofʉ, apopoha'o c'o ci temo s'a smopcoko.
english: Don't run and walk slowly lest you fall down.

tsu: mi'o co tonsoyʉ no mieci baito.
english: I want to see them right away.

tsu: te mai na teko hia oh ne teova?
english: How do you go to the block-house?

tsu: te'o yonto koyai ho oh ne teova.
te mai na teta hia oh ne veoing?
english: How does he go to the hospital?

tsu: teta coeconʉ ho oh ne veoing.
te mai na teko hia oh ne lanyi?
english: How do you go to Penghu?

tsu: la'o yonto hikooki ho ohne lanyi.
english: I go to Penghu by plane.
I go to Penghu by boat.

tsu: te'o nooyo to koyai no mayahe.
te yono coma 'o apo'o ho te oh ne 'oyonatmopsʉ?
english: How does apu'u go to school?

tsu: te nooyo to koyai no tacvo'hi 'o apo'o ho oh ne 'oyonatmopsʉ.
english: apu'u goes to school by train.

tsu: te yono coma 'o pasoya ho te oh ne kiokai?
english: How does pasuya go to church?

tsu: te yonto zitensa 'o pasoya ho oh ne kiokai.
english: pasuya goes to church by bicycle.

tsu: lako yonto koyai no mayahe ho oh ne 'oyonatmopsʉ?
english: Do you go to school by MRT?

tsu: o'a, mi'o nooyo to vaso ho oh ne 'oyonatmopsʉ.
english: No, I go to school by bus.

tsu: lako yonto zitensa ho oh ne 'oyonatmopsʉ?
english: Do you go to school by bicycle?

tsu: teno, la'o yonto zitensa ho oh ne 'oyonatmopsʉ.
english: Yes, I go to school by bicycle.

tsu: lako nooyo to kaothe ho lako oh ne kaoseong?
english: Do you go to Kaohsiung by High Speed Rail?

tsu: teno, la'o nooyo to koyai no smomacongo ho oh ne kaoseong.
english: Yes, I go to Kaohsiung by High Speed Rail.

tsu: ho teko oh ne thaitong, nenosi na te mayahehe 'o koyai ho hikoki?
english: Are you going to Taitung by train or by plane?

tsu: te'o nooyo to hikoki, mo mayahehe to koyai 'o hikoki.
english: I will take the plane because it is faster than the train.

tsu: teko nooyo no vaso hoci eno iachi poʉt'ʉcʉ no koyai ho teko oh ne kiokai?
english: Are you going to drive to the church or take the bus?

tsu: te'o iachi poʉt'ʉcʉ to koyai ho oh ne kiokai, te sonʉhe to vaso.
english: I will drive to the church because it is more convenient than the bus.

tsu: mo com'o to emoo soo 'o mo meoi no 'oyonamhia macocoma?
english: Is the market close to your house?

tsu: o'a te, la'o yonto 'otovai ho la'o oh to mo meoi no 'oyonamhia macocoma.
english: No, it is not, so I always ride the motorcycle to the market.
Is the post office close to the school?
Yes, it is within walking distance.
Is the restaurant close to the station?

tsu: c'o akameosʉ ho te i'mi ta toosva koyai ho coeconʉ.
english: It only takes five minutes after you walk out of the station.
I would like to visit you.

tsu: o'a te'o'so yon ta emoo, aiti ho mahohocma.
english: I am out today. How about another day?

tsu: te nana ʉmnʉ ho hocma? ta'o biebini ho ta'esi no cohzona.
english: Then, are you available tomorrow? I'll visit you tomorrow afternoon.
Sure, I will wait for you at home.

tsu: te'o peela loko'ing 'e fihngao soo, ta'o ocea poa tposʉa.
english: Would you mind if I do the voice recording? I would like to keep a record.

tsu: te'o peela sasing no poa televi?
english: Would you mind if I do the video recording?

tsu: o'a te, o'a mi'o yongho, maezo esko'o si macocoma ta emoo.
english: No, I am plain and the warehouse hasn't been tidied up yet.
Then I will just take photos.
Thank you for accepting the interview.

tsu: naho toocosʉ. Coma nan teko ocea cohivi?
english: You are welcome. What would you like to know?

tsu: coma na osoo la hioa ne mosoo n'a fionana?
english: What do you do when you are young?

tsu: mo'o la kengsaco, at'inghi mi'o co tosvo maitan'e.
english: I was a police officer but I am retired now.
Then, are you working at the moment?

tsu: mio maezo yon ta hosa na oko soo?
english: Do your kids live in the tribe too?
No, my kids are all living in the city.
Then, do you live by yourself?

tsu: mi'o aʉt'ʉcʉ to av'o ho zomʉ, la'o c'o acʉha teai 'oahngʉ'o.
english: I also keep a dog and a bird. They are my family.

tsu: mi'o maezo aʉt'ʉcʉ to ngiao, la'o koa o'te nama nac'o homo c'o noachi.
english: I have a cat too. I won't get bored with the company of my pet.

tsu: os'o ocea toocosi ho la hoseoyʉ ne noana'o 'e coo.
english: I would like to ask you about the taboos of hunting.

tsu: o'a mi'o nama bocbochio, 'a te'o yot'ingha na os'o cohivi.
english: I don't know much about that, but I will tell you everything I know.

tsu: pano peisiasi to la tititha hoseoyʉ ci macocoma?
english: Do you have any taboos about hunting weapons?
Our hunting weapons are untouchable to women.
Then, can women go hunting together?

tsu: o'a te, o'a la hioa to maamespingi na hoseoyʉ.
english: No, women cannot go hunting either.

tsu: pasoya, ok'a na viicio, teko n'a oh ne'e ho mhino.
english: pasuya, our home is out of rice wine, please go and buy some.

tsu: 'a panto mo n'a cono pania ne soiziva, 'anco te 'ahʉyʉ mhino!
english: There is still one bottle left in the kitchen, so there is no need to buy one!

tsu: moc'o cono pania, o'a te amso, ivaho n'a mhino no te yoso no pania.
english: One bottle is not enough for me, go and buy two more back.

tsu: te'o mhino no viicio, pano n'a?
english: I am looking for rice wine. Do you have any rice wine?
Yes! How many bottles do you need?

tsu: poa yoso no pania, hon'a cono cfoa ci fʉesʉ.
english: I want two bottles and a pack of rice.
Here is the rice, what else do you need?

tsu: te'o n'a maezo mhia fcoyo, pano?
english: I want some eggs too, do you have some?
I want to buy some clothes.
What kind of clothes do you like?

tsu: te'o mhino to mo nanʉhtʉ 'o soyosi.
english: I want to buy the clothes with short sleeves.
We have white and green ones too.
Please give me the clothes in green.

tsu: pasoya, mimo oh neno ne soni? Peohpeayofʉ?
english: pasuya, where have you been just now? Did you go exercising?

tsu: o'a, os'o to'osni 'o ba'i'o ho phieni 'o lasi emʉ'a ci macocoma.
english: No, I went grocery shopping for my grandma.

tsu: 'ia mamo maica. pano teko hioa ho yofna? oh tan'e teto eaabobonʉ.
english: No wonder! Are you available at night? Would you like to have a meal with me?
No, I want to buy some clothes.
Then, I will go with you.

tsu: yokeoaso, te pio na hophina ta chae?
english: Hello, how much is this bunch of vegetables?
The vegetables are $20 for a bunch.

tsu: te pio na hophina ta f'oe?
english: How much are these sweet potatoes?

tsu: te'o yoso no efʉta ci chae ho kinkini si f'oe poa aoseoseolʉ 30 na hophinasi.
english: Please give me two bunches of vegetables and thirty dollars of sweet potatoes.

tsu: pasoya, os'o ta'payo'a 'o 'empico'o, teko peela yovahneni a'o?
english: pasuya, I forgot to bring my pen. Can you lend me one?

tsu: teko peela yovahneni n'a a'o? ta'o c'o osna yoveia.
english: Can you lend me the pen for a second? I will return to you immediately.
Thank you and thank tanivu for me.

tsu: te'o yoveia 'e mo yoso ci tposʉ.
english: I want to return these two books.
No problem and what else do you need?

tsu: te'o i'vahon'a yovaho ta mo toyo ci tposʉ.
english: I would like to borrow these three books.

tsu: os'o cohivi, talʉa yoveia ho tena c'o miteohi.
english: Sure and remember to return them after three days.
You haven't returned me the eraser.
Then, why is my eraser missing?
Did you lend it to pasuya?
I don't know. I will go and ask her.
I will lend you my eraser first.

tsu: tanivo, isi yovahneni soo to pasoya 'e ocmʉyʉ ci yʉsʉ?
english: tanivu, did pasuya lend you this coat?

tsu: o'a s'a, 'a isi phini to ino'o.
english: No, my mom bought it for me.

tsu: mo totiski to ocmʉyʉ ci yʉsʉ to pasoya.
english: voyu's coat is the same as yours.

tsu: mo koa'onga 'o ocmʉyʉ ci yʉsʉsi, mo yopa h'onasi ta nooto.
english: His coat is black, so our colors are different.

tsu: tanivo, miko yovaho no peiso to pasoya?
english: tanivu, did you borrow money from pasuya?
Yes, I was supposed to return to him today, but I forgot to bring the money.
Then, when will you return the money?
I will return to him tomorrow.
Okay, I will tell pasuya for you.

tsu: la titho to tocʉfʉ ho te tʉtpʉtʉ to bohci, la titho to feo'isi ho te tʉtpʉtʉ to toevosʉ.
english: It is correct to catch mice through rangay and catch bamboo partridges through qjiulang.

tsu: 'ie ma mo maica, ko'ko o'a mi'o ahto ticono.
english: No wonder! I am mistaken and that's why I cannot catch any of them.

tsu: te'o no i'vaha pa'cohieni ho la moyai ta h'oepona.
english: Then I will teach you how to set up these two traps.

tsu: 'a teno, ta'o la ko'ko meelʉ tov'ohʉ no yoansoo.
english: Great! I will be able to catch the prey in the future.

tsu: mico taacvo'hi si kokozo ta chana, oh ne tvosiamacocoma ho mayo to poyave, teto n'a oh ne chana.
english: The grass in the fields is too tall. Go to the warehouse to take the sickle and let's go to the fields.

tsu: si soteona to apngo, 'a tako teolʉi.
english: It is next to the round basket. You will see it when you enter the warehouse.

tsu: bomemealʉ ho teko yaa, 'a mo na'no feofeo 'o poyave.
english: Be careful and don't get hurt. The sickle is very sharp.
My trap is under that tree.

tsu: mo'o moyai hoomzi, 'a os'o cohivi mo yoneno 'o h'oepona'o.
english: I make a mark here, so I know where my trap is.

tsu: 'a yongo eni, la titha yaa yoskʉ.
english: This is a fish trap which we put beside the river for fishing.

tsu: ok'a s'a yongomza, lamza c'o toalongo.
english: We don't have any fish traps there, so we catch fish with a fishing rod.

tsu: o'a mo'o la ahto toalongo, tako n'a la pa'cohivi a'o zoo?
english: I have never used a fishing rod before, would you mind teaching me next time?

tsu: ta'o lea, 'a tato no ipopohʉ toalongo.
english: Sure! Let's go fishing together next time.

tsu: ho mio ta'o pa'cohivi mooyai yongo.
english: I will teach you how to make a fish trap next time.

tsu: si longo soo mico yaa boecʉ ci yoskʉ, naho co e'tʉi.
english: Your fishing rod is moving. Isn't the fish on the hook? Pull it up!

tsu: 'otemoco, moso na'no tmaʉzʉ 'e 'apangʉ, te'o yon tan'e ho e'tʉ, teko n'a oh ta'e ho yaa ta 'ami.
english: Wait, the ship is rolling heavily. I am here to pull the fishing rod and you should go there to grab me the net.

tsu: 'a teko no e'oni tan'e na yoskʉ, te'o to'ono e'yʉ.
english: Pull the fish to my side and I will help you pull it up.

tsu: mainecomo maitan'e, co ngangcʉngcʉ 'e yoskʉ. ʉmnʉ ci hia tov'ohʉ.
english: Great! It is a bumper crop today with full fish baskets.

tsu: teto co maine'e ho angaezneni to maa'oahngoto.
english: Let's go back immediately and share it with everyone.
Stop playing and quickly sit in your seat.

tsu: mo maioemo maitan'e, te tosvo ho hocma, tato nʉthʉ mimiyo!
english: It's Friday today, we have a day off tomorrow. Let's go out and play together!
Great! Let's go to the riverside.
What day will it be tomorrow?

tsu: te maioteo ho hocma, tato peispak'i no mali ho atavei no cohzona ho hocma!
english: Tomorrow will be Wednesday. Let's go play ball tomorrow afternoon!

tsu: coma na tako hioa ho hocma?
english: What will you be doing tomorrow morning?

tsu: te maikayo ho hocma, temia yoyoso 'o ino ho ohne kiokai.
english: Tomorrow will be Sunday, I will be going to church with my mom.

tsu: mi'o mici teavto, te'o ohne tote'ia.
english: I feel like vomiting. I need to go to the restroom.

tsu: lema'cohio, mo congo 'e bʉyo'o, te'o ohne tote'ia.
english: Teacher, I have a stomachache. I need to go to the restroom.
May I go wash my hands?

tsu: tec'o mon'i tosvo, totea na'a hoco ohne'e.
english: It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.

tsu: lema'cohio, mo na'no congo co fngoo'o, te'o m'ea tosvo no atatvei no cohzona.
english: It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.
Okay, take care and go home.

tsu: lema'cohio, ta'o m'ea tosvo ho tena maiocni, ta'o poa aitneni to leaotothomʉ.
english: Teacher, I need to take a sick leave next Monday. I have to see a doctor.

tsu: mo congo 'o bʉyosi, mo yone tote'za.
english: She has a stomachache. She's in the restroom.

tsu: mo, congo 'o vihi to pasoya, mo m'ea tosvo maitan'e.
english: Teacher, pasuya has a sore throat. She took a sick leave today.

tsu: zoo mo'o vayaeana na a'o, mi'o co tomaska ta tonsoha.
english: My name is mo'o vayaeana, and I'm 10 years old.

tsu: zoo oko no coo soezopʉ neno na soo?
english: What ethnic group are you from?

tsu: zoo acʉhʉ coo soezopʉ na mimo conoemoo?
english: Are all your family members indigenous?

tsu: 'a zoo, zoo acʉhʉ coo a'toana 'e mimia conoemoo.
english: Yes, my whole family is Cou.

tsu: zoo acʉhʉ coo soezopʉ na conoemooso?
english: Are all your family members indigenous?

tsu: o'asa'a, 'a coo a'toana 'o amo'o, zoo pooto 'o ino'o.
english: No, my father is Cou, and my mother is Han Taiwanese.

tsu: zoo oko no sia na soo?

english: Is that your father? How old is he?

tsu: zoo amoso na tonoi? mico topioha?
english: Is that your father? How old is he?

tsu: o'as'a, 'a mameoi ta yoo, mico tomvoevʉha.
english: No, he is an elder of our tribe. He is 80 years old.

tsu: mio na'no mameoihe soo na ohaeva noso hahocngʉ?
english: Is your brother much older than you?

tsu: co noana'o ho o'te yopa baito, 'a mikocos'a asohco bankake?
english: I haven't seen you in a while. Have you grown taller?

tsu: te'o ohne pankongsʉ ho i'eima 'o lema'cohio.
english: I'm going to the office to see the teacher.
He's going to throw away the trash.

tsu: 'a mita yonto 'oyona yoohngozo, tata co yopa toosa'o no yoohngozo.
english: He's at the swimming pool. He's going to compete in a swimming competition later.

tsu: mo yoneno 'o sayongo? tenata co yopa toosa'o no peayofʉ.
english: Where is sayungu? She's going to compete in a running competition later.

tsu: 'a mita yonto lii-thang, te'o eno osa ho yooho'a.
english: She's in the auditorium. I'll go call her.
Let's go to the playground together.

tsu: te'o na'a mhia ocohiona, ta'o co i'eima soo.
english: I'll go buy lunch first, and then I'll meet you later.

tsu: teto eno yoyoso ho hafa na cʉyʉ!
english: Let's carry the lunch boxes together!

tsu: biebimi no mocmo, te'o i'eima 'o lema'cohio.
english: You find someone else, I'm going to find the teacher.

tsu: te yopa toosa'o no choeichio 'o tibosongo maitan'e?
english: Is tibusungu competing in croquet today?

tsu: o'ate, teta yopa toosa'o no smoepepe.
english: No, he's competing in high jump.

tsu: tako i'opo note yopa toosa'o hote 'ontookai?
english: Will you compete in the sports day?

tsu: 'a ta'o eno, ta'o i'opo to yopa toosa'o no toemayahe.
tako yoyafo no yopa toosa'o ho tena hiesi no 'ontookai?
english: Will you compete in the sports day?

tsu: 'a ta'o i'opo to yopa toosa'o no choeichio.
coma na tato hioa ho tena 'ontookai?
english: What will we do in the sports day?

tsu: tato yopa toosa'o no yopa ee'tʉyʉ.
english: We will compete in tug of war.
Will we sell food at the sports day?

tsu: ma miko mayo tomo ti-'i-ming, a'ʉmtʉ koici meemealʉ!
english: Congratulations on getting first place! You're amazing!

tsu: 'a mio, mita yonto hopo ho oengʉtʉ.
english: Yes, she's sleeping in her room.

tsu: o'amos'a, mita emoyafo, tena maine'e ho yofna.
english: No, she's not. She just went out and will be back in the evening.

tsu: 'a mita yone nikai, naho eno osa ho i'eima.
english: He's upstairs. You can go up and find him.

tsu: 'iama yapasoyongʉ, noana'va o'te aiti na soo, leako ʉm'ʉmnʉ?
english: It's yapasuyongʉ. I haven't seen you in a while! How have you been?

tsu: 'a lea'o na'no ʉm'ʉmnʉ! os'o i'eima soo ho toa ya'ei.
english: I'm doing great! I came to chat with you.

tsu: mita yonto 'oyona pei'i ho cmoecoyo to chae, te'o eno osa ho yooho'a.
english: He's in the kitchen cooking. Let me go call him.

tsu: 'a mita ohto emoo no teo'oa ho tʉtpʉtʉ to teo'oa.
english: She went to the chicken coop to catch chickens.

tsu: o'amos'a yonta emoo 'o ak'i, mo yone ezoyʉ,, temo yonta emoo ho totea.
english: Your grandfather is not at home. He's in the field. Wait for him to come back.

tsu: noana'va o'te aiti, ma mikoco yobankake.
english: I haven't seen you in a while. You've grown taller.

tsu: na'no kokaekaebʉ ho os'o aiti na soo ho miko cmʉ'ho.
english: It's so good to see you.

tsu: na eni te'o faeni moo ci 'ongeai, te siya no tvoyohoa.
english: Here's a pineapple for you. Put it in the refrigerator.

tsu: miko co noana'o o'te ohtan'e, te'o eho'ʉ ho toehongo bonʉ.
english: It's been a while. Let's have a meal together.

tsu: o'ate 'ahʉyʉ, te'oc'o mimo no 'ocea, teto ohto aemana ho yoya'ei.
english: No need to bother. I'll just have tea. Let's sit in the living room and chat.

tsu: 'aveoveoyʉ ho iko aʉt'ʉt'ʉca, te'o co maine'e.
english: Thank you for your hospitality. I have to go now.

tsu: isin'a ala choa si teo'oa, teko hafa maine'e ho oopopoha'va.
english: This chicken was just freshly killed. Take it home and enjoy it slowly.

tsu: teto na'a yopa esvʉtʉ no yopa baito ho ataveisi no cohzona ho hocma.
english: Can I make an appointment with you tomorrow afternoon?

tsu: 'oatee, teto esvʉtʉ no yopa baito neno?
teto esvʉtʉ ho yone 'oyonatmopsʉ zoo? tato tas'ongka.
english: How about meeting at school? We need to shoot a video.

tsu: ma tee eno ohne koba, ta'o sʉ'eʉsʉ to yʉsʉ no coo.
english: Then let's go to the community center. I'll wear folk costume.

tsu: la na'no yongho 'o yofoyonʉ ta hosa homo seolʉa no bʉvnʉ, tako totea ho tena bʉvnʉ ho i'eima a'o.
english: The cherry blossoms in our tribe are beautiful when they bloom. Come find me when the flowers bloom!

tsu: ma tee eno mooteo no hofongahoa, 'a tee eno ango poha'o!
english: That would have to wait until spring. It's too late, isn't it?

tsu: ma tako eno ohtan'e no mayasvi!

english: Alright! I'm looking forward to it!

tsu: te'on'a toocosi, mainci miko mici yoovei ta hosa ho h'oyonsoo?
english: May I ask why you decided to move back to the tribe?
I want to return to teach at the local school.

tsu: mainci o'te yone ngeesangsi ho ma'cohio?
english: Why not teach in the city?

tsu: la'o'so taaecingia 'e aesiiei hosa'o, yaeza 'ocea toovei 'e hosa'o.
english: Because I miss my hometown and I also want to give back to the tribe.

tsu: ci miko na'no meemealʉ tme'si,sia na moso ma'cohio soo?
english: You're very skilled at weaving, who taught you?

tsu: 'a i'e ba'i'o, 'a mita atva'esi meemealʉ tme'si ta hosa.
english: It was my grandmother, she is the most skilled weaver in our tribe.
How did you develop an interest in learning weaving?

tsu: 'a 'oahngʉ to h'oyonsovamza, la'o 'ocea poa ticngicngihi 'e h'oyonsova.
english: Weaving is a part of our culture, and I want to ensure its continuity.

tsu: mo na'no mafe 'e emi no ton'o eni.
ci miko na'no meemealʉ, mio noana'o ho isi teai?
english: You're really talented. Does it take a long time to make?

tsu: o'ate, tec'o cono mainsohʉ. la pe'eni 'o ton'o ho poa yompohoa, tac'o pei'i ho poa coyoa hoco hoyoha to apngo, poa na'a fosoa tac'o tiz'oz'a ho poa chomoa hoco hoyoha to kaiyo..
english: No, it only takes about a week. The millet first pounded into powder, and then poured into a large pot to cook, and then poured into the sieve grain utensils, cooled and kneaded by hand into a liquid, can be packed into the urn.

tsu: mi'o yaa coc'o ho pohe tan'e, 'a o'o iachia emʉ'a.
english: I have chili and corn, both grown by myself!

tsu: os'o ʉmnʉa 'e yʉsʉ eni, te sopioi?
english: I like this piece of clothing. How much is it?

tsu: mo ango pepe, te peela ake'a poa cʉecʉ?
english: It's too expensive. Can't you lower the price a bit?

tsu: o'ate te'o sonsolo hoci ango cʉecʉ.
english: No, if I lower it further, I'll lose money.

tsu: 'oatee! ma te'o eno yaa 'emo koa'onga ci yʉsʉ.
english: Alright then, I'll take a black piece of clothing.

tsu: te'o yaa 'e fo'fo ho i'e tngoo.
english: I want this knife and this pot.

tsu: mo acʉhʉ soposioeso, na eni o'o iachia tiemoca ho teai, tee asansana peela noana'va titha.
english: It's a total of 2000 dollars. I handmade these, and they are guaranteed to last a long time.

tsu: ta'o eʉsvʉta to nanghia'o ho poa mhino, te meelʉ asohco cʉecʉ?
english: I'll introduce my friend to buy. Can you give a further discount?
Alright! I'll give you a 20% discount.

tsu: ohtan'e ho bobaito! 'e isi phieni ci yʉsʉ ho ceopngo.
english: Come and take a look! We sell clothes and hats.

tsu: isi sose'toeva meemohʉ 'emo coni ci yʉsʉ, soposifoo 'emo toyo.
english: One piece of clothing is 350 dollars, three pieces for 1000 dollars.

tsu: tec'o coni 'e te'o phini, fii'sio a'o nomo faeva.
english: I'll just buy one piece, please give me a new one.

tsu: 'aveoveoyʉ soo, mi'o mici mhia naveo hohʉ'eʉca ho foo toe'opi no ma'fʉ.
english: Hello, I would like to buy sticky rice and braised pork with maqaw pepper.

tsu: co psʉepʉngneni 'o naveo, panton'a chong-yoo-ping, teko mhino?
english: The rice is sold out. I have tana pancakes, would you like to buy them?

tsu: 'oatee, poa cono oachia, ta'o i'vaho ohtan'e ho mhia naveo.
english: Alright, please give me one. I'll come back next time to buy rice.

tsu: 'oatee, te'o to'oni soo ho cfoa to efoco, te someemohi.
english: Okay, I'll pack it in a bag for you. That'll be 50 dollars.

tsu: mo mai pito ne mi'o ohne 'oyonatmopsʉ.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

tsu: ahoi tmopsʉ, yʉmeʉmʉ to 'oyomia tmopsʉ 'o lema'cohio, mainca 'o letaayaezoi, "yac'ʉ! m'ohkoyo!"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

tsu: mo seolʉa no tmopsʉ, isi pa'cohivi to lema'cohi tala hia tmasvʉtʉ no boacoo.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Cou language of numbers.

tsu: mimza tmo'ofehni to lema'cohio ho engha, mimza paso tmasvʉtʉ.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.

tsu: mo man'i 'o os'o pelʉi ci h'oe'ea coo.
english: I have learned many Cou languages.

tsu: la'o hohocmasi ohne 'oyona tmopsʉ, la'o hohocmasi aʉsvʉtʉ boacoo, te'ola esvʉtneni to ino'o.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Cou language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

tsu: mo cihi 'o ohaeva'o atai 'o ongkosi, mitaco tomaska veaocni.
english: I have a brother, his name is atai, he is 11 years old.
We study in the same school.

tsu: a'o ho ohaeva'o lamza na'no kaebʉ pasonaeno.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

tsu: la'o kaebʉ yohngozo, homo seolʉa tosvo, lamza nʉtʉ 'o mimza conoemoo ho yohngozo.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

tsu: la'o kaebʉ ho mi'o ea faeva ci nanghia, temiala melʉ toehongo pasonaeno ho yoohngozo.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.
There are five people in our family.
There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

tsu: a'o ho amo, ino, ohaeva no hahocngʉ ho ohaeva no mamespingi lamza noteoyono.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.

tsu: mo bankake 'o amo'o, zoo lesmo'eisi 'o amo'o.
english: My father is tall and he is a policeman.

tsu: mo kʉehoi 'o ino'o, zoo leaotothomʉ 'o ino'o.
english: My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

tsu: 'o amo hola yontoemoo lasi oaneni boacoo a'mi.
english: My father speaks the ethnic language with us at home.

tsu: ho lamza tosvo lamza acʉhʉ maine'e ne hoehongo.
english: We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

tsu: a'o ho ma'ahaeva lamza tʉtpʉtʉ to kio.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.

tsu: la'o na'na ʉmnʉa 'o coo to emoo'o.
english: I like our family very much.

tsu: mimza yoyoso 'e ino ho covnʉ maitan'e.
english: I went out with my mother today.

tsu: na'no tatposa 'e pepe homo hie, o'amo soyʉmʉ o'amo mo'ei, na'no sohoyo 'e poepe.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

tsu: mimza yootamo yaakokozo ci ceoaho yaa bobonʉ, sliʉa ta hia co feango, na'no noyano.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.
In the afternoon, the sky turned red.
I asked my mother why the sky is red.

tsu: yainca ta ino, teasonʉ cmo'ho na cmoeho.
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

tsu: ok'a ci meipeipi ta engʉca homo yofna, mico yoyafo si congeoha.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

tsu: smaimio ta ceono maine'e, mi'o mi'ono to feohʉ m'ea tooyokeo.
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

tsu: atva'esi ʉmnʉ ote esmi na cmoeho, mi'on'a mici mimiyo.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

tsu: 'o la'o yoni ci 'oyonatmopsʉ mo nocmo'o to emoo'mia, la'o hohocmasi coeconʉ ho ohto 'oyonatmopsʉ, maezo la'o coeconʉ ho main'e.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

tsu: o'a mo meoisi 'o lamza yoni ci 'oyonatmopsʉ, o'amo botngonʉ 'o 'o'okono tmopsʉ, lamza acʉhʉ yopa bobohngʉ.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

tsu: la acʉhʉ yo'eteyono to 'oyonayoyaso 'o 'o'oko, toehongo peispak'i to ma'li, noteoyono ho aomomotʉ'ʉ.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

tsu: la maezo tes'opo 'amia 'o lema'cohio ho peispak'i, zoo cono emoo 'e 'oyonatmopsʉ.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

tsu: lamza hohocmasi ateoteop'ʉcʉ, la acʉha tosi'nga ho poa cofkoya 'ola 'oyonavenkio.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

tsu: pantola mahisi to pethʉ'ta, pantola tosi'ngi to aokokoyongo.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

tsu: lamza na'a tosi'nga 'o maococolili to 'oyonatmopsʉ, lamza aangaeza 'ote hioa, hohocmasi na'no cofkoya 'o 'oyonatmopsʉ.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

tsu: ne hocma, mi'o ohto hoehongo ho aitia 'o ak'i.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

tsu: mico noana'o ho o'ana mimza ahto yopa bobaito, os'o na'na taecingia.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

tsu: aiti to ak'i a'o, osnia pa'ni to vahatʉ a'o, pema to 'ocea.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

tsu: na'no cohʉmʉ 'o isi emʉ'a to ak'i ci vahatʉ, aʉmtʉ na'no mafe.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

tsu: os'o yaeza ʉmnʉa 'o 'ocea to ak'i, maezo mafe ho isi ima.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

tsu: co cohiona, mimza iepoepohʉ 'o ba'i ho apapeipei'i tote ana no cohzona.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

tsu: na'no toemamave 'o bai homo apapeipei'i to 'oanʉ no cohiona, mo yaa yoskʉa, yaa teo'oa, yaa posiahʉa, maezo yaa kokeot'ee.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

tsu: oepʉngʉ ocohioni, mimza ohto chachae ho toa chae
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

tsu: man'i 'o isi yaa to ba'i ci f'oe, ocei ho t'ocnga faeni a'o, pahafneni a'o maine'e.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

tsu: mimza yopa tooyokeo, tamzala vohvaho no ta'esi ho aiti hin'i.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

tsu: maitan'e hafa to lema'cohio amia ho ohto 'oyonayoansoo, mimza bitoyange to phingi ho mhia ki'po.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

tsu: oh'aemonʉ to 'oyonayoansoo, yainca to lema 'cohio "e to'cosi zoo mazozomʉ, f'ohosi zoo mafkofkoi, temo iachi bobaito."
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

tsu: la'o'so smoyo to fkoi, ko'ko o'a te'o baito to fkoi.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

tsu: man'i 'o os'o aiti ci zomʉ, mo meiavovei to ma'e'evi 'o mazozomʉ, maezo baito to poko cimo yoto feongo to evi ho oengʉtʉ.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

tsu: 'o 'aemona to 'oyonayoansoo mo ya ckio, 'oma ho e'oho, o'amo'ocola ahto baito tamo maica ci yoansoo, kaebʉ ho mi'o bobaito maitan'e.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

tsu: man'i 'o os'o ho'ongki, ta'o poa aitneni to ino ho amo.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

tsu: tamzala nʉthʉ 'e ino ho amo ho i'vaho ohtan'e no ta'esi.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

tsu: h'otosvo maitan'e, momza yoyoso 'o ohaeva no'o mamespingi ohne maibayo ho aiti 'o amoconi.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Chiayi to visit my uncle.

tsu: mimza 'i'mi ne taipaho ho yonto koyai no tacvoh'i ho ohne maibayo.
english: We took the train from Taipei to Chiayi.

tsu: mimza co sʉcʉhʉ ne maibayo, poʉtʉcʉ to koyai 'o amoconi ohto 'letosvakoyai ho sopoti amia.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

tsu: o'amo nomcovhi to 'oyona letosvakoyai 'o emoo to amoconi, homo poʉt'ʉcʉ to koyai moc'o osni sʉcʉhʉ.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

tsu: com'o to emoo to amoconi pantomo meoino leaʉtʉcʉ moatʉ'nʉ, mimza smopayo to zitensa ho ohto leaʉtʉcʉ moatʉ'nʉ.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

tsu: yonto meoino leaʉtʉcʉ moatʉ'nʉ, hafa to amoconi a'mia ho p'onʉ 'to moat'ʉnʉ ho smopayo to oma.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

tsu: mico yofna, mimza evasʉzʉ ho ohto 'iciva ho eabobonʉ.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

tsu: mo man'i 'o koyai to 'iciva, ko'ko mimzac'o yonto 'otovai ho ohto ic'o.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

tsu: ne temzaco mongoi, 'iamaihe peo'eoza 'o otovai', ko'ko mimzacoc'o yonto vaso ho mongoi.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

tsu: mimzaco yoovei ne taipaho, o'a imza cohivi 'o 'otovai to amoconi isico nana ahta elʉa.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

tsu: ne mo'ona'a oko mosola yone tfoya'o emoomia, mo'ocola tmopsʉ, co noezoho ne maibayo, momeacola nochʉmʉ ne'e.
english: When we were young, our family lived in tfuya'o. After I started school, we moved to Chiayi and have been living in the city ever since.

tsu: mo'ocola tmopsʉ to taingakoo, mi'o tmopsʉ ho aʉsvʉtʉ to ceoceona no h'oyonsova ta coo, peela cohivi mo a'ʉmtʉ mav'ov'o 'o h'oyonsova ta coo ta taivang.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

tsu: ko'koeno, ieni homo tosvo ta tonsoha maitan'e, mimza yoyoso 'o ohaevano'o ahocngʉ ho maine'e to hoehongomia ho bobaito to mamameoi, ocia cohivi na ceoceona no h'oyonsova ta coo.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

tsu: mico'so tonvoevʉhʉ 'o mameoi, at'inghi mioc'on'aso mais'a haah'o ho isi aiti.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

tsu: os'o toocosi coma na osko peela ci e'e, mita na'no empompohso ho mita boa coo, mita maezo meelʉ boa maaya, boa pooto ho boa sbokono.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in cou, as well as Japanese, Chinese and Bunun.

tsu: i'mi ta hia'o toococosi ho cohivi, 'iama mita ahoi ho mohtan'ala oko ho aʉsvʉtʉ boa coo ho boa maaya zoo sbokono 'o vcongʉsi.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, his wife is an Bunun, and he knows many Chinese at work, so he can speak so many languages.

tsu: ne miza maica yopepeahngʉyʉ, 'e mameoi mo eʉsvʉsvʉtʉ tomo man'i ci tela hia e'ohʉ ho ea foo ci a'a'aosna.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

tsu: e'vono o'a imza peela a'sʉftona acʉha ta'hongi, at'inghi mimza boemi to sooci ho loko'in, tenamiala ivaha ʉmnʉ ci ta'lʉi.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

tsu: ahoi ne mo'on'a oko ho o'a o'ola cohivi na iachi ceoceona no h'oyonsova ta coo, a'ʉmtʉs'a iachi pa'hikokoe'i.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

tsu: fihta hia aosohco man'i na isi cohivi, cohivi ho coo 'e iachi, mo na'no h'onasi ci coo a'ʉmta atva'esa itanveni ci a'a'aosna.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a cou is unique and something to be proud of.
My younger brother is going home this evening.

tsu: mimza yoyoso 'o ba'i ohto 'iciva ho mihia teo'oa, akoeva no pei'i note mafe ci oyoefona 'o ohaesa.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

tsu: mimza esmi 'lemhinochai, mo man'i 'omo ʉmnʉ ci chae.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

tsu: mimza mihia miciveongo, f'oeofoo, ho teikon.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

tsu: yainca to taoke tomo nocmo'o ci momhinonchae, "'e 'ongeai ho kemomo'o mo na'no cohʉmʉ 'o. ma akei mhino!"
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

tsu: mimza esmi tola momhino foo, yainca to taoke, "teko mihino no coma? mo meoisi ho simeo 'e teo'oa maitan'e, mo se'toeva 'emo coni."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

tsu: isi anga pepea to ba'i, toocosi 'o taoke te ʉmnʉ oci ake'a poa cʉecʉa.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

tsu: at'inghi isi yainca to taoke mic na'no cʉecʉ, 'anate peela ashca poa cʉecʉa.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

tsu: yainca tomo nochipi ci taoke, mihino ta yosko'o, mo meisi ho cʉecʉ 'e yosko'o.
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

tsu: mimza atavei mihino to teo'oa maezo mihino to yoskʉ, cono panka 'o imza pe'i ci chae ne mimza co maine'e.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.
After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

tsu: psoemio to memeno 'o ohaesa yainca, akameosʉ o'ate azoo tosva 'e heetai, ta'esi no nicio nate'o mee'lʉ maine'e.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

tsu: yainca to ba'i mico toeman'i tate ana, co acʉhʉ yabobonʉ!
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

tsu: mimza yoho'ʉ 'to ma'o'oahngʉ maanananghia, acʉhʉ tioo tomo ʉmnʉ ci hia yaabobonʉ oyoefonʉ.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

tsu: mo cihi 'o mimza tmahmʉhmʉsko zoo pasoya 'o ongkosi, la loema'payo'ʉ mahafa 'to macocomasi.
english: I have a classmate named pasuya, he often forgets to bring things.

tsu: ho la tmopsʉ, la mi'ono tomo tmahmʉhmʉskʉ ho yoevaho to lesmapayo'ʉ ho letposi.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

tsu: y'ʉnʉskʉ, i'popsohʉ, i'toteoho, lahen'a yovahneni to nacocoma.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

tsu: ati'nghi pantolata koici hioa, lata asngʉcʉ yovaho to macocomahe ho oh'te yooveineni.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

tsu: ko'ko o'a na ohe'la ocia poa yovahneni to macocomahe.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.
One day, we all went on an outing together.

tsu: momza seolʉano emo'osnomaica, akameosʉ na'no mici te'i 'o pasoya, at'enghi 'iamamita tapayo'ʉ mahafo tola titha mahisipcoo ci kami.
english: On the way, pasuya wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

tsu: mita mi'osno to mihini tmahmʉhmʉsko 'e pasoya ho yovaho to letithamahisi teta akoyo no ohse'o, atng'ihi mo acʉhʉ mainca, maezo o'a mi'os'a mahafo.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

tsu: mitaco amio tmomongsi 'e pasoya. mita sʉ'no ho mainca, maincis'a o'te poa yovahoa to letithamahisi.
english: pasuya burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

tsu: yainca to mihimn'i tmahmʉhmʉskʉ, 'a miko no'so 'ote iachi mahafo, a'vinano inante yovahneniso ci macocoma, ana tekos'a ahta yoveineni.
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

tsu: mico hocma tec'o ohoto 'oyonatmopsʉ, mo sʉfeʉnʉ 'o pasoya ohto 'oyonatmpsʉ, ita acʉha yoveineni to mihimni tmahmʉhmʉskʉ 'o ohtala yovaha ci macocoma.
english: The next day at school, pasuya arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

tsu: mi'osno to mihimn'i tmahmʉhmʉskʉ ho 'aveoveoyʉ 'e pasoya, mainca, ta'ocola iachi mahavo no macocoma, 'aveoveoneni to mimza tmahmʉhmʉskʉ ihingn'i yovahneni to macocoma ne aoyosi.
english: pasuya apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.
My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

tsu: mo'on'ala oko, la e'ohʉ homo yofna 'o amo ho amoconi, la smo'iei ho teos'ofʉ.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

tsu: tac'o tiskova, taheco hafa maine'e 'o ihe poomia ci yoansoo.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

tsu: la asvʉtʉ mayo to fozo, aasvʉtʉc'o voyʉ, la aasvʉtʉ mayo to toevosʉ.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

tsu: lahe na'nosino aoeva angaeza na'a, taheco angaezneni to ma'o'oahngʉ.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

tsu: la'o 'aoko m'ea viho to amo, mici fiho to amo ho e'ohʉ.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

tsu: yainca to amo ieni ho ta'ocola saasmoyʉskʉ tasicola yoyosveni ho i'ohʉ.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

tsu: 'o hahocngʉ to hoehongo la maezo melʉ titho to h'oepona ho boepono to yoansoo, la meelʉ moyai to vomʉ no h'oepona ho tocʉvʉ.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

tsu: 'o amo'o la saiho homo moyai h'oepona no evomʉ, yainca to amo, la titha boepono to toevosʉ eni, tetola yaeza yoe'ia 'o lasi p'ecihi to yoansoo, la sia to hoyosi to yoansoo 'o h'oepona.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

tsu: akoyo no aopcio mel'ʉ fiho to mamameoi ho e'ohʉ, la'o hohocmasi aʉsvʉtʉ boepono, c'o osni yaa momza to h'oepona'o ci yoansoo.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

tsu: mi'oni to amo'o yainca takola ahtoo'te leyaafoo ci coo.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

tsu: mi'oco saasmoyʉskʉ, os'o ngoevi 'o fsyonoaʉlʉ fiho to amo ho e'ohʉ.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

tsu: maine'e to hoehongo angaeza 'o isi poomia ci yoansoo ho angaezneni to ma'o'oahngʉ.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

tsu: yainca to amo, teto'la to'aveoveoyʉ nola pocengi, tela ko'ko man'i na teto'la tov'oha ci yoansoo.
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.

tsu: mi'o poha'o ne taseona ne te'o toatmopsʉ.
english: I was late for school this morning.

tsu: me mi'o ohone 'oyonatmpsʉ, os'o ta'payo'a hafa 'o tvotposʉa.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.

tsu: ok'a ci os'o hafa ci macocoma.
english: I didn't bring anything with me.

tsu: mo seo'lʉa no tmopsʉ, mimia iepoepohʉ baito to tposʉ 'o mimia tmepoepohʉ.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

tsu: sio'lʉa no hʉsvʉta, yoevaha to mimia tmaepoepohʉ 'o 'oyomza tmopsʉ'o ho 'oyomza smaofsoso.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

tsu: mi'oni a'o to le'aotothomʉ ho yainca, "takocola yoe'oo'oo no ta'esi, 'ote na'la 'aoko poha'o!"
english: The teacher told me, "Wake up earlier next time and don't be late again!"

tsu: 'o nanghia'o zoo pasoya, zoo maezo oko no coo to psoseongana.
english: My good friend's name is pasuya, and he is also an Cou child.

tsu: lamia iepoepohʉ toatmopsʉ to yoo ne saviki.
english: We study together in the saviki tribe.

tsu: lamia asngʉcʉ iepoepohʉ tma'lʉ to mameoi hola ehohamo, lamia acʉhʉ na'no melʉ boa coo.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Cou proficiently.

tsu: mi'o na'no bankake ho maezo na'no noyʉnʉ, mita na 'no potisi 'e pasoya ho maezo na 'no kʉehoi.
english: I am tall and overweight, while pasuya is short and thin.

tsu: mo na' no peiseayayokeo 'o pasoya, la toehonga ʉmnʉa.
english: pasuya is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

tsu: maitan'e zoo meesi no 'ontoo 'to 'oyona tmopsʉ, man'i 'o isi hioa ci yopatoosa'o to 'oyona tmopsʉ.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

tsu: moyaa yopa e'tʉyʉ, mo'potʉ to mali, toosa'o no mayahe, 'otole, pono to yanosoyo.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.

tsu: ne mi'o seo'lʉa no peyaofʉ, mi'o smopcoko, meoino yohmoyo 'o ka'li.
english: When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.

tsu: at'inghi mi'o yac'ʉ, mi'o acʉ'cʉnʉ peyayofʉ.
english: But I stood up and continued running forward.

tsu: ne mi'oco seolʉa no toepaezomo mo acʉhʉ na'na kokaekaebʉ.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

tsu: 'evono o'ami'o somayahea, at'inghi mi'o na'na kokaekaebʉ, maica ho os'oco aepʉnga na'e yopa toosa'o.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

tsu: ne hocma a'o ho amo imia osa aiti 'o amo'o coni.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

tsu: isi eʉsvʉta a'mi, 'o patingsoha to sofʉ mo meoino ah'ʉtʉ.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

tsu: ne isi seolʉa no teovahi 'o sofʉ. i'mi to patingsoha to sofʉ ho sopeohʉ.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

tsu: mo mahafo to foo 'oachomo ho fi'i 'o amo'o ho faeni to amoconi.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

tsu: a'o ho amoconi mimia yontola yoni amiocni ho yopeahngʉyʉ, mo man'i 'o isi aangaezneni ci h'oehohanva.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

tsu: aoyosi ne teo'co mongoi, emomoengʉa to amoconi ho mi'oco yobankake, maezo asohco mʉʉlʉlʉ.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

tsu: os'o yainca, "toteni ho tac'o yov'o 'o t'angosi, maezo sio ohta emoo'o no ta'esi."
english: I said, "When your foot gets better, come to our house next time and visit us."

tsu: nemoso tonsoha no 2022, 'o 'oyonatmopsʉ kaingi ho toʉsvʉsvʉtneni te peela aleonga poa ongko ta coo 'e mivonso.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

tsu: os'o toocosi 'ola aoesiesi mi'osno to 'oyonatmopsʉ ho pnanfi no tata'ia aleonga poa boa cooa 'e mivnsooo ta coo ci foinana to yoo ci paso'e yasiongo.
english: I interviewed pasu'e yasiungu, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

tsu: mimia yo'tasvʉtʉ hotena seolʉa no tosvo ho ohto emoosi ho aiti.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

tsu: to taicosi ne os'o tococosi, isi eʉsvʉta na isi i'mizi to ongkosi, isi yaeza poa hongneni 'o iachisi emoo ho yoosi.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

tsu: os'o toocosi maincis'a na'no bitotonʉ no taezohi si ongkoso, o'amo ʉmnʉ 'o mico aesiei cila hia tmopsʉa?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

tsu: yainca to pasoya, "na aʉmtʉ ongkoto 'aeno 'e isi oanenicoo ho tposi ci ongko na aʉmtʉ ongkoto. 'e ongko'o zoo ongko to 'oahngʉ'o, zoo ongko to mimia conoemoo, zoo ongko mia, tata'ia te asohco botngonʉ nate pela e'lʉa na iachi ongko."
english: pasuya said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

tsu: ne hocma mimia yoyoso 'e ba'i ho ohtola toehonga hoteyoni mhinmhino te soovai, 'o ba'i mo mahafo to isi iachia emʉ'a ci machachae te soovai, maezo moyai to mafe cila ana to coo ci 'oanʉ ho faeni tomo batngonʉ.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

tsu: ihe na'na ʉmnʉa 'o soovai to ba'i, 'o coc'o ho tomato mo botngonʉ 'omo mhino, botngonʉ 'omo oso ho oothomʉ to isi pei'i ci chae.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

tsu: 'oisi pei'i ci chae hʉngʉ ho ofi na'no mafe, ho i'o isi titheni to foo fozo ho toeteoyoni pei'i 'o ma'fʉ ci foo, 'o na'aosnasi ihe na'no kaeba tomo botngonʉ ci coo, acʉhʉ ohto soovaimia ho bitoyange.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

tsu: nemo seolʉa no apapeipei'i 'o ba'i, mi'o yonto ciengonasi ho meokokosʉ tomo sococafi ci coo. mi'o yonto ciengonasi tmonoi moozoyʉ, "'e chae c'o acʉha iachia emʉ'a, acʉhʉ yʉ'ʉ'ʉmni ci chae, aopcio mhino!
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

tsu: 'o macocomamia c'o osnia psʉepʉngneni, yainca to ba'i, "moc'o acʉhʉ i'mi ho miso to'osno."
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, "It's all thanks to your help."

tsu: 'emo maica ci hi'hioa, mi'o tov'ohʉ ta nat'ʉca no cacʉfea ta coo ho mao'to'tohʉngʉ no ma'o'oanʉ, avinano peela cohivi na ngoseo tala soovai.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

tsu: aiti 'e ba'i ho lata aʉmtʉ soekaibʉ ta ma'o'oanʉ, os'o iachia na'na itanvevi ho yaa ta'osnia.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.
the thing stuck between the teeth
at the foot of the mountain
witchcarft appliance (witch doctor use it for treatment)
peeling the bark of a tree
dry (e.g., drying clothes in the sun)
pack up (imperatives, as in pack up)
fishing for fish and shrimp by cage
lift off (as in lift off the lid).
burn (as in burning the hair of prey)
marry to a non-ethnic clan member
in the process of (doing something or happening)
